name: o-toluic acid

The addition of the methyl group (toluene) to benzene typically raises the melting point due to an increase in the molecular weight and van der Waals forces, by approximately 28°C. The carboxylic acid functional group (benzoic acid) raises the melting point significantly due to the possibility of hydrogen bonding and the increased molecular weight. The effect of the carboxylic acid group on benzene is an increase of about 117°C (note that benzoic acid has a melting point of 122.41°C). When combined in o-toluic acid, the methyl and carboxylic acid groups will both contribute to an increased melting point, but since they are ortho to each other, there is likely to be a steric hindrance effect that somewhat lessens the elevation expected from the sum of both groups' effects in isolation. We consider a slight decrease due to steric hindrance, estimating a 5°C reduction.
Prediction: The predicted melting point is 5.5 (base benzene) + 28 (methyl group) + 117 (carboxylic acid group) - 5 (steric hindrance) = 145.5°C, which does not match the actual melting point of 104.35°C. Upon reconsideration, the steric effect might be greater, and there may be other interactions and structural effects in ortho-substituted aromatic acids that reduce the melting point more than initially estimated. Further analysis and comparison to similar compounds would be needed to provide a more accurate prediction.
